Storage of half a year of millet likely corresponds to what a family at Jiangzhai would have consumed over the course of a year, reserving some seeds for planting at the end of the season, but only if their diet was also supplemented by other resources. We know that hunting continued to form an important strategy during the early Yangshao period, as did gathering of wild resources (
 
  52
 ). Aside from a few households, a substantial investment in storing additional grain to buffer against failed harvests does not appear to have been a key strategy at the site. For a site that was located at a near 100% probability of being in its thermal niche, this seems like a reasonable strategy.
